49. Newman criticiseS, not without justice, the inconsistency between this stanza and the last. ‘ Magnum illa terrorem intulerat’ mars the effect of the picture of imperial calm. Jove, it would seem, was frightened; the ultimate victory was due to other gods. Horace almost seems to sorget that he has localised the majcsty of heaven in Jupiter. His object now is to exalt Pallas, the representative of mind. The power of heaven was cowed, but the mind was unshaken.
